In my project we are using quite some fluent api's and it would be nice if the compiler / language can partly invert generic parameters based on passed arguments. This to make code better readable.

```
namespace Test
{
	public class Program
	{
		public static void Main()
		{
			var api = new Original<int>();
			
			// this is what I have to write
			var extended = api.Extend<int, long>();
			
			// but it would be nice if I could write the following because the first generic parameter could be inverted from the passed argument
			// var extended = api.Extend<long>();
		}
	}

	public interface IMyFluidApi<T>
	{
		void Print();
	}

	public class Original<T> : IMyFluidApi<T>
	{
		public void Print() => Console.WriteLine(typeof (T).FullName);
	}

	public class Wrapper<T, TExtended> : IMyFluidApi<T>
	{
		private readonly IMyFluidApi<T> _original;
		public Wrapper(IMyFluidApi<T> original) => _original = original;
		public void Print() => Console.WriteLine(typeof (TExtended).FullName);
	}

	public static class MyClassExtensions
	{
		public static IMyFluidApi<T> Extend<T, TExtended>(this IMyFluidApi<T> api) => new Wrapper<T, TExtended>(api);
	}
}
```

VSF_TYPE_MARKDOWNTool Tips is reporting that a type variable with the same name as a class is the class.

Example code:
```
void Main()
{
	var thing1 = new MyFoo();
	var thing2 = new Record();
	var thing3 = new Bar();
	Console.WriteLine(thing1.Method(thing2));
	Console.WriteLine(thing1.Method(thing3));
}

public abstract class Foo
{
	public abstract int Method&lt;T&gt;(T input) where T : IFoo;
}

public interface IFoo
{
	bool Set { get; }
}

public class Bar : IFoo
{
	public bool Set =&gt; false;
}

public class Record : IFoo
{
	public bool Set =&gt; true;
}

public class MyFoo : Foo
{
	public override int Method&lt;Record&gt;(Record input)
	{		
		if (input.Set)
			return 1;

		return 0;
	}
}
```

Tool tips is showing that for this line: `public override int Method&lt;Record&gt;(Record input)` 'Record' is the class Record and not a type variable called 'Record', which is confusing. If things were as the tool tips is reporting than this line: `Console.WriteLine(thing1.Method(thing3));` should throw a compiler error. But the program runs just fine.

